gomodel:SYNGO_4806  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Figure 2: Overexpression of Slitrk5 promoted excitatory synapse formation.\n\nFigure 3: Knockdown of Slitrk5 reduced synapse numbers in cultured hippocampal neurons.\n\nFigure 4: SLITRKs interact with PTPRs (Slitrk5 was not tested in the annotated paper due to lack of suitable antibodies, but was tested in PMID:26004511).\n\nAuthors conclude;\n\"Although the precise mechanism governing synaptic adhesion between Slitrks and LAR-RPTPs remains elusive, the fact that Slitrks and LAR-RPTPs serve double duty as inducers of either excitatory or inhibitory synapses places these protein families at center stage in the control of excitatory-inhibitory balance, which is critical for neuronal function (34).\". Experimental description: Methods\nArtificial synapse-formation assays, cell-adhesion assays, and cell surface labeling assays were performed with HEK293T cells as previously described (22, 30). (ref.) Primary rat hippocampal neurons were cultured from E18 embryos.\n\nOverexpressed proteins:\n- \"pCDNA1-Slitrk3 encodes full-length mouse Slitrk3\"\n- \"pGW1-Slitrk3 encodes full-length human Slitrk3\"\n- \"pCMV5-Slitrk4 encodes full-length human Slitrk4\"\n- \"pCMV5-Slitrk5 encodes full-length Slitrk5\" (species not mentioned)\n- \"pCMV5-Slitrk1-monomeric Venus (mVenus) encodes full-length human Slitrk1\"\n- \"pCMV5-Slitrk2-mVenus encodes full-length human Slitrk2\"\n- human PTP-δ-Ecto (NM_002839, aa 21-1174) (traced back to PMID:20139422)\n- human PTP-σ-Ecto (NM_130854, aa 30-1167) (traced back to PMID:20139422)\n\n- Selected human species based on the overexpressed PTPRS in the cell-aggregation assay." ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2286-1587" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-4973-5732" ;
        dc:date           "2022-08-30" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_4806" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_9606" .

